    "question_id" : 185893,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I personally prefer VisualVM. One of the features I like in VisualVM is heap dump comparison. When you are doing a heap dump analysis there are various ways to go about figuring out what caused the crash. One of the ways I have found useful is doing a comparison of healthy vs unhealthy heap dumps.</p>\n<p>Following are the steps you can follow for it :</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Getting a heap dump of OutOfMemoryError let's call it &quot;oome.hprof&quot;. You can get this via JVM parameter HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError.</li>\n<li>Restart the application let it run for a bit (minutes/hours) depending on your application. Get another heap dump while the application is still running. Let's call it &quot;healthy.hprof&quot;.</li>\n<li>You can open both these dumps in VisualVM and do a heap dump comparison. You can do it on class or package level. This can often point you into the direction of the issue.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>link : <a href=\"https://visualvm.github.io\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://visualvm.github.io</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 16743892,
      "reputation" : 740,
      "user_id" : 12980819,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/fzeyWVR6.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Falchio",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12980819/falchio"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1699977110,
    "creation_date" : 1699977110,
    "answer_id" : 77482024,
    "question_id" : 185893,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I'm using IntelliJ IDEA profiler in Ultimate version.\nIn IDEA, press the Shift button twice.<br />\nIn <code>Actions</code> tab write - &quot;profiler&quot;.<br />\nChoice row &quot;profiler&quot; with icon.<br />\nThen <code>Open snapshot..</code> button.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 26349558,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 20007391,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0f640c1992051d41de034107e3c04d26?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "nswagg",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/20007391/nswagg"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1716218785,
    "creation_date" : 1716218785,
    "answer_id" : 78507459,
    "question_id" : 185893,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You may get some value out of the Oracle <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/troubleshoot/tooldescr008.html#:%7E:text=HPROF%20is%20a%20tool%20for,in%20ASCII%20or%20binary%20format.\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Java Platform, Standard Edition Troubleshooting guide</a>, which details the <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/samples/hprof.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">HPROF: A Heap/CPU Profiling Tool</a>. It can be used to receive relevant information from from the JVM, like CPU usage sampling/times and memory allocation. You can take a look into that file with the tool and glean some high-level information.</p>\n<h2>Invoking the HPROF Tool</h2>\n<pre><code>$ java -agentlib:hprof ToBeProfiledClass\n$ java -Xrunhprof[:options] ToBeProfiledClass\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Obtaining Heap Allocation Profile</h2>\n<p>Shows allocation for various parts of the program</p>\n<pre><code>$ java -agentlib:hprof=heap=sites ToBeProfiledClass\n</code></pre>\n<h2>HPROF Help</h2>\n<pre><code>$ java -agentlib:hprof=help\n</code></pre>\n<p>The files are usually large and docs recommend <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/troubleshoot/tooldescr012.html#BABJGJBI\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JHAT</a> for visualizing the outputs of the heap dump (Also mentioned <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/185926/20007391\">above</a>). Can figure out what parts of your program are eating your heap memory and maxing out CPU usage.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2965471,
      "reputation" : 1075,
      "user_id" : 2518705,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/0XaQ5.gif?s=256",
      "display_name" : "RAM237",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2518705/ram237"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1730150310,
    "creation_date" : 1730150310,
    "answer_id" : 79135131,
    "question_id" : 185893,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Opening it with <a href=\"https://www.ej-technologies.com/jprofiler\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JProfiler</a> helped me a lot.</p>\n<p>Shows you the Heap Walker with all the threads, packages, classes and relations between them, so you can navigate, walk the incoming/outgoing references and visualize.</p>\n<p>There is a plenty of guides on using it, so getting the general idea on dump analyzing should be enough to start using it.</p>\n<p>It requires a paid license, but has 10 days of free trial.</p>\n"
